{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1fb7f5e3-27ba-452b-8165-1c542553ed32","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root, shared by all 3 projects)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <!-- Required for dotnet test integration on .NET 8 SDK -->\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n## 2. TRX reporting\n\nThe old `--logger trx` is a VSTest concept. For MTP, add the TRX extension to each test `.csproj` (or a shared `Directory.Packages.props` if using central package management):\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.3\" />\n```\n\n## 3. CI command\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is passed to the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner.\n\n**Key points:**\n- `EnableMSTestRunner` makes each test project a standalone executable using MTP instead of VSTest.\n- `OutputType Exe` is required since each project now hosts its own test runner.\n- `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is needed on **.NET 8 SDK** so `dotnet test` knows to use the MTP protocol (this becomes the default in .NET 9+).\n- Your existing `Microsoft.MSTest` 3.8.0 package references stay unchanged.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e8618df8-0691-4a08-a647-f55343653f72","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate 3 MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). They're on .NET 8 SDK and use `dotnet test --logger trx` in CI.\n\nLet me provide a concise, accurate answer based on my knowledge of MSTest 3.8.0 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey points for MSTest 3.8.0 migration to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n1. **Project-level changes**: Add `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to each test project, or better yet, use a `Directory.Build.props` to set it consistently.\n\n\n2. **MSTest 3.8.0 already includes the Microsoft.Testing.Platform** - no additional package references needed beyond what they already have.\n3. **CI command changes**: The `--logger trx` syntax changes slightly. With MTP, you need `--report-trx` instead of `--logger trx`.\n4. Since they want consistent properties across all projects, a `Directory.Build.props` is the right approach. For MSTest 3.8.0, the Microsoft.Testing.Platform is integrated into MSTest starting from 3.x, so enabling it just requires setting `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>`.\n5. Each test project needs `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` since they become self-contained executables. For TRX logging with MTP, you'll need the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package, and the CLI flag changes from `--logger trx` to `--report-trx` when running the exe directly, though `dotnet test` might handle this differently. `dotnet test -- --report-trx` should work, though I'm second-guessing whether the TRX extension needs to be explicitly added or if there's a property that pulls it in automatically with MSTest 3.x. Let me consolidate the approach using Directory.Build.props to keep things consistent across all three test projects.\n\nConfiguring shared properties...\n\nFor TRX reporting, I can either add the NuGet package directly or use an MSBuild property. With MSTest 3.8.0 on .NET 8, I need to verify which approach is correct and what the exact property name should be. So the property I need is `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` set to true, and then I can run `dotnet test -- --report-trx` to generate the TRX report in CI.","outputTokens":1818,"requestId":"A037:2FE433:BFEDA8:DFF3E8:69FE84F9"},"id":"a4486675-b0e0-4ecd-9608-446a82988ec3","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:40.453Z","parentId":"7bf059a9-a2ea-49b3-9f20-6d5c996e55c8"}
